Notes: Praetor at some unknown date after 41 (Ulpian Dig. 1.14.3, Barbarius** cf. Dio 48.34.5** Suidas s. v. Bocpo (I)XLZto4).
Governor (Pr. or Propr.) of Asia before 90, possibly before 100 B. C. (I. v. Priene 121** see Magie, Roman Rule in Asia Minor 1579).
CIL 1(2).2.20: (quais)toris or (prai)toris. Third century B. C.
Tac. Ann. 3.75, a praetorius** cf. Fast. Cap., Degrassi 60f., 141, 528f., his son held the consulship in 5 A. D.
CIL 1(2).2.803-ILS 3141. Possibly Aemilius Papus, Pr. 205, or Paullus, Pr. 191, less probably Regillus, who was M. f., Pr. 190.
CIL 1(2).2.20** (quais)toris or (prai)toris. Third century B. C.
CIL 1(2).2.814-ILS 906. Late Republic or Early Augustan period. See PIR(2) 1.187f., no. 967.
A praetorius, cited by Messalla Rufus, Cos. 53, as an example of one who was placed on the pyre and returned alive (Plin. NH 7.173).

Pr. Urbanus The Praetor who killed a portentous woodpecker and died shortly afterwards (Plin. NH 10.41** Frontin. Str. 4.5.14, with the names L. Aelius and Laelius** cf. Varro in Non. Marc. 518 L** Val. Max. 5.6.4, on the Pr. Aelius, who died at Cannae).
Pr. Urbanus CIL 1(2).2.825-ILS 5742. Probably late second century.
A Praetor in the late Republic or the Early Augustan period (CIL 6.1364-ILS 943** see PIR(2) 2.29, no. 155). Also a Legate of M. Antonius.
CIL 14.2603-ILS 902. Praetor of uncertain date, but after 46 B.C.
Praetor in the late Republic or the Early Augustan period (CIL 6.1374-ILS 917** see PIR(2) 2.151, no. 686). Died before 12 B. C.
An unknown Claudius of early date who is said to have sold the Camerini into slavery (Val. Max. 6.5.1).
A praetorius who saved his father, an Antonian supporter and a prisoner after Actium at Samos (App. BC 4.42).
Spoke in a praetorian place in the Senate in 63 (Sall. Cat. 50.4), perhaps a Praetor before 67.
CIL 1(2).2.819. The Tribune of the Plebs in 57 went into exile for ambitus (Cic. Planc. 75** Schol. Bob. 165 Stangl), but may have returned and resumed his career in 49.
A Praetor or Propraetor in Asia before 90, possibly before 100 B. C. (I. v. Priene 121, cf. p. 551** see Magie, Roman Rule in Asia Minor 2.1579).
CIL 6.1282-ILS 882, date uncertain, but possibly after 31. See PIR(2) 2.240, no. 987.
A Praetor in the late Republic or the Early Augustan period (CIL 1(2).2.2515** see PIR(2) 2.17, no. 96).
Pr. Urbanus, probably before the period of Sulla (CIL 1(2).2.2516 -ILS 9376).
CIL 1(2).2.826. Late Republic. Date and identification uncertain.

Praetor, at an uncertain but quite early date, who undertook a self-imposed exile rather than fulfil a portent that he should be king (Val. Max. 5.6.3** Plin. NH 11.123** Ovid Met. 15.565ff.** see RE 5.2565).
A commander in operations in Liguria, probably Pr. or Procos. (Frontin. Str. 3.2.1). Unidentifiable.
Pr. or Promagistrate, probably in Macedonia. Honored at Athens (BCH 6. 278, no. 3), and an epoptes at Samothrace (CIL 3.12318-ILS 4054), without title.
CIL 1(2).2.823, and 824** see 110, Promagistrates. A Praetor and then Proconsul in Spain in the late second century.
Plin. NH 7.44. Date quite uncertain.
A Praetor in the late Republic or the Early Augustan age (Val. Max. 9.12.8** Plin. NH 7.184).
See above, on L. Iulius Mocilla, and L. Livius Ocella.
A praetorius in the army of Brutus whom Atticus aided after Philippi (Nepos Att. 11.2). See below, on L. Livius Ocella.
Cic. Arch. 9. Praetor at an uncertain date, probably before 82.
Munzer identifies him with L. Iulius Mocilla (above), and with the [GREEK] who was condemned by Brutus at Sardis in 42 (Plut. Brut. 35).
Named as Pr(aetor) on coins of L. Livineius Regulus (Grueber, CRRBM 1.580** cf. Cic. Att. 3.17.1).
Commander in a campaign, probably in Greece or Sicily, date and title unknown (Frontin. Str. 3.5.3).
CIL 1(2).2.837-ILS 905. See PIR 3.173, no. 135. Late Republic or Early Augustan period.
Pr. Designatus. Convicted of ambitus about 90 B. C. by T. Iunius L. f. (Cic. Brut. 180** see Niccolini, FTP 422).
Pr. and then Procos. when he governed Hither Spain in the late second century (CIL 1(2).2.840** see 110, Promagistrates).

Praetor or Propraetor in Asia before 90, possibly before 100 B. C. (I. v. Priene 121** see Magie, Roman Rule in Asia Minor 1579). Munzer however believes that he was a Legate under Sulla and identifies him with the M. Plautius, Prefect of an allied fleet, which he was bringing back from Asia when he committed suicide at the news of the death of his wife Orestilla (Val. Max. 4.6.3). See below, Prefects of uncertain date.
Grandfather of the future emperor and father of the Consul of 5 A. D., his career reached only to the praetorship (Suet. Galba 3.3** on SEG 1.169, see Miinzer, RE).
A praetorius in 44 (Porphyrio on Hor. Sat. 2.2.49f.** cf. Acro and Comm. Cruq. ad loc.). Certainly in the Senate (Cic. Fam. 12.29.2).
Probably the father of Servilius Vatia Isauricus, who held command of some province, probably Macedonia, and was honored at Olympia (Cic. Verr. 2.3.211** I. v. Olymp., 329).
Vell. 2.71.2. See 42, Prefects.

CIL 1(2).2.838, and 839-ILS 8208. Probably the Monetalis of ca. 89 B. C. M'. SERGIUS Pat. (17) Pr. and then Procos. when he governed Hither Spain in the late second century (CIL 1(2).2.840** see 110, Promagistrates).

Named, probably as presiding officer, in a fragmentary decree of the Senate discovered at Trikkala in Thessaly (Giannopoulos, Eph. Arch. 1934-35, 149, no. 2 [pub. 1936]** cf. L. Robert, Etudes Epig. et Phil. 287f., note 1). Probably before the middle of the second century.
Listed as a senator in Joseph. AJ 14.220, where the order favors the assumption that he had praetorian rank in 44.
Consul Designatus under the Second Triumvirate, who committed suicide because of threats from Octavian (Suet. Aug. 27.3** cf. on Uttiedius Afer, Augur and Cos. Desig., Inscr. Ital. 1.1, Tibur, 134).
Date uncertain, but late Republic or Early Augustan period. CIL 1(2).2.812** see PIR(2) 1.94, no. 569.
Varro RR 2.4.2. See 71.
Senator, perhaps aedilicius, named in the SC de Panamareis, Viereck no. 20.
Late Republic or Early Augustan period. CIL 1(2).2.814-ILS 906** see PIR(2) 1.187f., no. 967.
Cos. 75 Attained all the highest offices (Cic. Off. 2.59). No specific proof that he held the aedileship.
Val. Max. 8.3.1. He may be identified with the Titius mentioned in Plin. NH 31.11 (but cf. C. Titius Rufus, Pr. 50), and father of the Consul of 31.
The date of his praetorship is uncertain but probably came soon after 76 (App. BC 4.47** Themist. p. 453 D** see Cichorius RS 203).
CIL 1(2).2.800. Leased a construction for Aesculapius as Aedile and approved it as Praetor.
Ann. Epig. 1948, no. 65: PR EX S C, inscribed on an archaic peperino altar. The names Cominius and Geminius have been suggested.
CIL 1(2).2.817. A Curule Aedile in the late Republic. Date and identification uncertain.
CIL 1(2).2.22, Aedile of the Plebs. Name on a milestone on the road to Ostia, probably before 200.
CIL 1(2).2.37, dated in the third century, but not certainly original at Rome.
Late Republic or Early Augustan period. CIL 1(2).2.826** see PIR(2) 3.203, no. 494.
CIL 1(2).2.829-ILS 5802, Aed. Pl. A milestone on the Via Tiburtina, date uncertain.
CIL 1(2).2.37, dated in the third century, but not certainly original at Rome.
Ai[d. cur.], CIL 1(2).2.807, date uncertain but in the last century of the Republic. With [Po]stumius A. f. (see below).
Senator, perhaps aedilicius or tribunicius, listed in 39 B. C. in the SC de Panamareis (Viereck no. 20).
Cos. 76 Attained the highest offices (Cic. Off. 2.59). No specific proof that he attained the aedileship.
Cos. 91 Attained all the highest offices (Cic. Off. 2.59). Not specific proof that he held the aedileship.
Aelian NA 9.62. Date and identity uncertain.
Ai[d. cur.], CIL 1(2).2.807, date uncertain, but in the last century of the Republic. With (Cn.? O)ctavius Cn. f.
CIL 1(2).2.800: Leased a construction for Aesculapius as Aedile and approved it as Praetor.
Held office in the late Republic or the Early Augustan period. CIL 1(2).2.812** see PIR(2) 1.94, no. 569.
Held office before 31 (CIL 6.1364-ILS 943** see PIR(2) 2.29, no. 155).
Pr. - Held office in the late Republic or Early Augustan age, and died before 12 B.C. (CIL 6.1374-ILS 917). See PIR(2) 2.151, no. 686, where Epulo is interpreted as a priesthood, not a cognomen.
Held office in the late Republic or the Early Augustan period. CIL 1(2).2.814-ILS 906. See PIR(2) 1.187f., no. 967.

One of a group named by Cicero as examples of persons who held the tribunate in one year and became Legates in the next (Leg. Man. 58, 66 B. C.). Metellus may have been either Creticus, Cos. 69, or Nepos, Tr. P1. 68, and a Legate of Pompey in 67, or Celer, Cos. 60.

A Lex Aebutia, probably tribunicial, barred the author of a law from holding an office established by it. This law precedes 63 (Cic. Leg. Agr. 2.21** Dom. 51), but may be after the Gracchi (see however Niccolini, FTP 411, on Liv. Per. 58). If Aebutius lived in the second century he may be the author of the law which introduced the formulary process (Gaius 4.30, FIRA 2.156** see Wenger, RE 6.2859).
One of a group named by Cicero as examples of persons who held the tribunate in one year and became Legates in the next (Cic. Leg. Man. 58, 66 B. C.). See CIL 1(2).2.1441.
Carried a Lex de sponsu (Gaius 3.121-123, FIRA 2.127** 4.22 and 109, FIRA 2.154 and 175) which preceded a Lex Furia on the same subject (see below, on Furius). See Niccolini, FTP 396f.
Held office in the late Republic or the Early Augustan period. CIL 1(2).2.2515. IIII vir i. d. at Volsinii.
Held office in the late Republic or the Early Augustan period. CIL 12. 2. 826** see PIR(2) 3.203, no. 494.
One of a group named by Cicero as examples of persons who held the tribunate in one year and were Legates the next (Cic. Leg. Man. 58, 66 B. C.).

No title preserved. Author of a Lex Fabia de plagiariis (Cic. Rab. Perd. 8** cf. Apul. Met. 8. 24, Corneliae legis** Coll. 14.2-3** Dig. 48.15** C. Th. 9.18** C. 9.20** Inst. 4.18.10). See Niccolini FTP 437.

Held the tribunate after Munatius Plancus Byrsa in 52 and before 44 (Cic. Phil. 13.27** cf. 11.13).? FABIUS (2) No title preserved. Author of a Lex Fabia de plagiariis (Cic. Rab. Perd. 8** cf. Apul. Met. 8. 24, Corneliae legis** Coll. 14.2-3** Dig. 48.15** C. Th. 9.18** C. 9.20** Inst. 4.18.10). See Niccolini FTP 437.

No title preserved. Carried a law limiting amounts of single legacies to individuals (Cic. Balb. 21** Verr. 2.1.109** Gaius 2.225-226, FIRA 2.90** Ulpian 1.2, FIRA 2.262** Fr. Vat. 301, FIRA 2.531** Inst. 2.22, pr.). It must be dated before the Lex Voconia in 169 (Gaius 2.226, FIRA 2.90). See Lange 2.255, who suggests 183 B. C.

Cos. 72 One of a group of persons named by Cicero as examples of holding a tribunate in one year and becoming Legates in the next (Leg. Man. 58, 66 B. C.). He might be identified with Lentulus Marcellinus, Cos. in 56, if the latter was really a plebeian.
No title preserved. Carried a Lex de sponsu (Gaius 3.121-123, FIRA 2.127). See Niccolini FTP 396f. See above on Appuleius and Furius.

No title preserved. Carried a Lex de sponsu (Gaius 3.121-123, FIRA 2.127** 4.22 and 109, FIRA 2.154, and 195** Ulpian fr. in FIRA 2.308f.) which preceded a Lex Cicereia and followed a Lex Appuleia (see above on these). See Niccolini, FTP 396f.

Author of a law providing for IIII viri among the magistrates of Petelia (CIL 10.113, 114-ILS 6468, 6469). Niccolini (FTP 428) suggests a date before the Social War, but Rudolph (Stadt und Staat im alten Italien 94f., 118, note) follows Hardy in attributing it to Cinna in 87 (Some Problems of Roman History 286ff.). No title preserved.
No title preserved. Author of a law to regulate the amount of a sponsio before the centumviri (Gaius 4.95, FIRA 2.173). See Niccolini, FTP 447.

Author of a Lex Licinia, probably tribunicial, and later than the Lex Aebutia (see above), which barred the relatives of a man who established an office from serving in it. It must precede 63 (Cic. Leg. Agr. 2.21** cf. Dom. 51).

A Tribune of the Plebs who was censured by a Censor named Acilius (Fronto Ad M. Caes. 5.41-42, 83 N). Note: No Censor of this name is known. Borghese therefore suggested that he was the unknown Censor of 64. There was however no lectio Senatus that year (Dio 37.9.4). The name Atilius, if it is meant, would bring into consideration the Censors of 247, 234, and 214. Cichorius (Untersuch. Lucil. 26f.) suggests Cornelius the Censor of 147. See Niccolini, FTP 438f.
A tribunicius who secured the conviction of P. Sextius, Pr. Desig., for ambitus (Cic. Brut. 180). Before the period of Sulla.
No title preserved. Author of a law, carried before 113, exempting persons who were absent on public business from prosecution during their absence (Val. Max. 3.7.9). See Niccolini, FTP 416.
A Lex Glitia dealt with unjust provision for children in wills (Gaius, Dig. 5.2.4). Date, author, and magistracy uncertain. See Niccolini, FTP 447.
A Lex Hostilia permitted actions at law by representatives in cases of theft (Gaius 4.82, FIRA 2.170** Inst. 4.10** Dig. 50.17.123). Carried in the period of the legis actiones (Niccolini FTP 410).
No title preserved. Author of a law to regulate money-lending (Fest. 268 L.** Non. Marc. 89 L** FOR 1.28 and 166). See Niccolini, FTP 400, who suggests a date in the period of Cato the Censor.
No title preserved. Author of a Lex Licinia de actione communi dividundo (Dig. 4.7.12). Date and office remain uncertain. See Niccolini, FTP 448.

No title preserved. Author of a bill to regulate the selection of Vestal Virgins by the Pontifex Maximus (Gell. 1.12.10-12). His date may be earlier than that of the moneyer L. Papius (6), who appears to refer to some law, but Berger (RE, Supb. 7.402) refers this law to C. Papius (5), Tr. P1. in 65.
Held office either before 42 or between 40 and 32. CIL 6.1460 -ILS 887.
His law calling upon the Pr. Peregrinus to provide for the election of III viri Capitales to exact the sacramenta (Fest. 468 L) must be dated after 241 and before 123 (Niccolini, FTP 396).

Author of a law requiring consecrations of buildings, areas, and altars to be specifically ordered by the people (Cic. Dom. 127-128). Probably after 174 (cf. Liv. 40.52.1) and before 154 (Cic. Dom. 130 and 136). See Niccolini, FTP 403f.

No title preserved but certainly a Tribune of the Plebs. Carried a Lex frumentaria which abrogated the Lex Sempronia (Cic. Brut. 222** Off. 2.72). Miinzer (RE) suggests a date before the law of Saturninus in 100, but Niccolini (FTP 426f.) holds that annulment of the laws of Saturninus and of Drusus brought the Sempronian law into force again, and the Octavius mentioned in Sallust (Hist. 1.62 M) is the Tribune of 133. He dates Octavius between 91 and 81.
No title preserved. Author of a law regarding attendants for Aediles of the Plebs (CIL 6.1933-ILS 1923** cf. Niccolini, FTP 445, late Republic).
No title preserved. A Lex Ollinia is mentioned in Gaius (4.109, FIRA 2.175).

No title preserved. Author of a law defining the status of children of marriages between Romans and non-Romans (Gaius 1.78-80, FIRA 2.24** Ulpian 5.8, FIRA 2.268). Since it applied to Latins Niccolini (FTP 424) is inclined to date it before 90 B. C.

No title preserved. A Lex Plaetoria (not Laetoria, RE, Supb. 7.398) to protect young men and minors from fraud is attested by Cicero (Off. 3.61** ND 3.74) and by the Lex Iulia Municipalis (line 112** termed Lex Laetoria in the oration of Claudius de aetate recuperatorum, FIRA 1.286). References to such legislation in Plautus (Pseud. 303f.** Rud. 1380-1382) have suggested that it precedes the date of the Pseudolus in 191 (Niccolini, FTP 400f.** Weiss, RE, Supb. 5.578** Buck, Chronology of the Plays of Plautus 4, 96, 105). See Bagnani, Phoenix 6 (1952) 73.

No title preserved. Author of a law under which A. Postumius Albinus, Cos. 180, as Duovir, dedicated an altar to Verminus (CIL 1(2).2. 804-ILS 4019), and an altar found in the Largo Argentina (MarchettiLonghi, Bull. Corn. 61 [1933] 163-194).

Carried a plebiscite defining the attendants of the Pr. Urbanus (Censor. DN 24.3** cf. Plaut. Epid. 25-27** Varro LL 6.5** Gell. 3.2.4). Weiss (RE, s. v. "Lex Plaetoria," no. 1) dates it before 241. Perhaps it was occasioned by the institution of the Pr. Peregrinus (Niccolini, FTP 396** Bruns, FIR7 45).

The authors at three different periods of the three Porcian laws cannot be identified with certainty, nor did they with certainty hold the tribunate of the Plebs. All three regulated corporal punishment and the right of appeal of Roman citizens (Cic. Rep. 2.54). The first may perhaps be attributed to Cato the Censor (see Fest. 266 L** FOR 1.182-184), a second to a Porcius Laeca (Grueber, CRRBM 1.151), and a third of uncertain attribution forbade scourging a Roman in the city (Sall. Cat. 51.21** see Grueber CRRBM 2.301). One Porcian law permitted condemned persons to go into exile (Sall. Cat. 51.40). See Niccolini, FTP 424-426** Botsford, Roman Assemblies 250-253.

No title preserved. Author of a law, dating probably before 32, which regulated the appointment of municipal prefects (CIL 9.2666-ILS 6515** 10.858-ILS 6359** 10.5405-ILS 6125** cf. CIL 9.422, in 32 B. C. - Degrassi 254f.). See Niccolini, FTP 444f.
Author of the Lex Papia de iure patroni et de bonis libertorum (Gaius 3.42, FIRA 2.109). Date, person, and office uncertain.
CIL 1(2).2.837-ILS 905** PIR 3.173, no. 135. Late Republic or Early Augustan period.
Author of a law, in force in 80, which imposed penalties for unfounded prosecutions (Cic. Rose. Amer. 55** Schol. Gron. 309 Stangl). See Niccolini, FTP 433f.
Pr. - Varro in Gell. 13.12.6. Conjectures regarding the date vary from 87-81 (Niccolini, FTP 432f.) to after 70 (Cichorius, RS 201f.** Dahlmann, RE, Supb. 6.1176).

The Tribune whose summons Varro, when III vir Capitalis, refused to obey (Gell. 13.12.6). Probably not a Cato but a Laeca or a Licinus (Cichorius, RS 201). A Porcius Laeca, Monetalis before 103, might have held the tribunate between 95 and 90 when Varro was from 21 to 26 years of age (Cichorius, above** Niccolini, FTP 428).
CIL 1(2).2.835** cf. Cic. Fam. 13.15.1. Late Republic.

Dig. 11.5.2.1. Author of a law limiting wagers to contests virtutis causa. The date is uncertain but precedes 81, if the Lex Cornelia on the same topic was carried by Sulla. No title preserved. See Niccolini, FTP 433.

Dig. 11.5.2.1 and 3. Author of a law limiting wagers to contests virtutis causa. The date is uncertain but precedes 81 if the later Lex Cornelia was carried by Sulla. No title preserved. See Niccolini, FTP 433.
No title preserved. Author of a law regulating the assignment of provinces to Quaestors (Cic. Mur. 18** Vat. 12** Schol. Bob. 145 Stangl). See Niccolini, FTP 437f.

No title preserved. Author of a law regulating appointment of guardians in the provinces (Gaius 1.185, FIRA 2.44** Ulpian 11.18, FIRA 2.275). The date is uncertain, but may come after the Iulian law of 46, and may have been carried by the Tr. P1. of 43. See Niccolini, FTP 443f.
CIL 1(2).2.812** see PIR(2) 1.94, no. 569. Late Republic or Early Augustan period.
Quaestor and then Proquaestor in Macedonia (see I. v. Olymp. 328, probably before 55).
Quaestor or Praetor in the third century B. C. (CIL 1(2).2.20** see above, Praetors).
Quaestor ca. 60. Candidate for the aedileship of 54 (Cic. Plane. 29).
Quaestor Urbanus before 28 B. C. (CIL 1(2).2.810). See PIR(2) 1.7, no. 54.
Late Republic or Early Augustan period. CIL 1(2).2.814-ILS 906. See PIR(2) 1.187f., no. 967.

No title preserved. Senator (Cic. ND 1.15, cf. 58, and 66, dramatic date 77), and friend of the orator Crassus (Cic. De Or. 3.78, dramatic date, 91). Niccolini (FTP 427) suggests that he held the tribunate before 90, but he may have been enrolled in the Senate by Sulla.
CIL 8.24583-ILS 8963. Late Republic.

date_source_text: before Leges Iuliae abolishing manus iniectio?
Notes: No title preserved. A Lex Vallia (Gaius 4.25, FIRA 2.155) preceded the Leges Iuliae abolishing manus iniectio.
An Aemilius as Quaestor built the Pons Aemilius (Plut. Num. 9.3). Doubted by Platner-Ashby, s. v. "Pons Aemilius."

Quaestor in Spain, named on coins of Urso, Myrtilus, and Baelo, dated by Grant to 44 and 43 under Sextus Pompey (From Imperium to Auctoritas 24f.). He also issued coins at Lilybaeum in Sicily (Ibid. 25). See Mommsen, RMW 375, note 28.
Brothers who attained the quaestorship, probably in the 70's (Cic. Brut. 242).
Brothers who attained the quaestorship, probably in the 70's (Cic. Brut. 242).
CIL 6.1364-ILS 943** see PIE2 2.29, no. 155. Served as a Legate under M. Antonius.
Quaestor before 46 (Auct. Bell. Afr. 34).
Senator, probably quaestorius, and fellow-tribesman of Varro (RR 3.2. 1), and a friend and correspondent of Cicero.
Scriba under Sulla's dictatorship and Quaestor Urbanus under Caesar's (Cic. Off. 2.29** cf. Sall. Hist. 1.55.17 M).
Senator, perhaps quaestorius, named in the SC de Panamareis (Viereck, no. 20).
A young senator, perhaps a quaestorius, in 82 (Plut. Sulla 31.1-2**cf. Schol. Gron. 337 Stangl).
Quaestor in Asia before 70 (I. de Delos 4.1.1858 bis-CIL 1(2).2.816** cf. Cic. Verr. 2.1.85).
I. de Delos 4.1.1632, before 100 B. C.
Quaestor in Asia where he restored roads built by the Consul Aquillius in 129 (CIL 3.479-1420111** 3.14202 -IGRP 4.1659-ILS 5814). See PIR(2) 1.193f., nos. 989, 990.
CIL 6.1282-ILS 882** see PIE2 2.240, no. 987. Son of Cicero's enemy, P. Clodius.
(not in RE) Probably in the late Republic. CIL 1(2).2.2515, also a Jill vir i. d. at Volsinii.
Senator, perhaps quaestorius, named in the SC de Panamareis, and the SC de Aphrodisiensibus (Viereck, nos. 20 and 19, resp.).
Late Republic or Early Augustan period. CIL 1(2).2.837-ILS 905** see PIR 3.173, no. 135.
Cos. 69, Pr. 72 Cicero in 70 describes his quaestorship as recent (nuper** Verr. 2.3. 182** cf. 2.1.36 and 99** Ps.-Ascon. 234 Stangl). His career had probably been delayed by the civil wars.
CIL 6.1460-ILS 887** see PIR 2.363, M 336. Either before 43 or between 40 and 34.

Quaestor in Spain in the late Republic (CIL 6.1446** cf. C. Livius named on coins of Vesci in Spain, Grant, From Imperium to Auctoritas 379f., who suggests a date ca. 40, and refers to L. Cella, named in Bell. Afr. 89.5, and the [GREEK] mentioned as a subordinate commander in Spain in that year by Appian in BC 5.54).
Cos. 75 CIL 1(2).2.832, on the road from Nursia to Spoletium.
CIL 1(2).2.827, before 90 B. C.
Q. Desig. in inscriptions on coins of 37 (Grueber, CRRBM 1.593f.).
CIL 1(2).2.832, with L. Octavius, who was probably the Consul of 75. On the road from Nursia to Spoletium.
Quaestor in Asia, at some date in the first century B. C. (I. v. Magnesia 155).
Lucilius 467-468 M. Under this name Lucilius satirized some Quaestor whose real name is lost. See Cichorius, Untersuch. Lucil. 317-320, possibly Tuticanus Gallus (cf. Caes. BC 3.71).
Elected Tribune of the Plebs for 50, and therefore a quaestorius. Convicted of bribery (Cael. in Cic. Fam. 8.4.2).
Served as Quaestor under M. Terentius Varro Reatinus (Varro LL 5.1** cf. 7.109), but the date is uncertain. See Cichorius, RS 203f.
Senator, perhaps quaestorius, named in the SC de Panamareis (Viereck no. 20).
CIL 1(2).2.841. Late Republic.
Varro LL 6.90. The date is after 242, but remains otherwise uncertain. See Sobeck 73.
Q. Desig. in inscriptions on coins of ca. 37 B. C. (Grueber, CRRBM 1.591f.).

CIL 1(2).2, p. 764, no. 383 e. Grant (26) suggests the above identification with the Praetor of 67 or 68.

CIL 12. 2, p. 761, no. 384 o. Late Republic.

CIL 1(2).2, p. 764, nos. 382, commentary, and 383 c. Bahrfeldt interprets Por. as referring to the Portus of Panormus. For Cato in CIL Grant reads Cat. Q. (26f.) and suggests that M. Porcius Cato was Quaestor in Sicily. This is impossible since he was fully occupied in Rome (see 64, Quaestors), but C. Porcius Cato, Tr. P1. 56, remains a possibility.
CIL 1(2).2, p. 764, no. 383 n. Grant (27, note 3) suggests the quaestorship of the Praetor of 49, P. Rutilius Lupus.
